[1] Detailed update
Date: Sun, 8 Apr 2012
Source: Masrawy.com [mach. transl, edited].
http://www.masrawy.com/News/Egypt/Politics/2012/april/8/4927858.aspx

FMD Report: 72 000 suspected cases, 15 000 deaths
-----------------------------------------------------
According to confirmed reports from the departments of veterinary medicine in the various governorates, there seems to be a decline in the daily incidence of FMD; from thousands of new cases per day, they are now counted in the hundreds.

The report, received by Engineer Mohammad Reza Ismail, Minister of Agriculture and Land Reclamation, from the General Organisation for Veterinary Services [GOVS], states that [the most recent infected governorates] are North Sinai (one case) and the Red Sea (71 cases). No cases have been reported from South Sinai.

According to Dr. Suhair Abdel Kader, Head of the Central Department for Preventive Medicine, the cause for the continued emergence of new cases per day is due to non-compliance, by the breeders and owners, with the requirements banning the movement of animals between farms and provinces and other bio-security measures, These include the need to separate sick animals from healthy ones as well as separating suckling calves from their dams.

According to the report, the total number of suspected cases, since the onset of FMD on 26 February 2012, is 72 272 of which 14 948 died - predominantly baby calves. Mortality in older animals is much lower, namely 2 - 3 percent.

The report emphasized that about 75 percent of the cases, namely 54 173, have recovered. There are 1569 veterinary units, scattered all over the country, which are engaged in the clinical treatment of the remaining 18 108 recovering animals. There are ongoing efforts by the MinAg and GOVS to monitor the health of animals and restrict contacts between foci of FMD.

The highest numbers of suspected cases have been recorded in the governorates of Gharbia and Dakahlia, with - respectively - 25 895 cases (3973 deaths) and 10 389 (1912 deaths) reported. Gharbia [=West] includes the largest concentration of dairy farms in Egypt. The figures of sick and dead animals from other governorates were the following: Alexandria 2400 (229), Minya 1973 (434), Suez 5306 (343), Qalyubia 1294 (244), Buhayrah 4382 (1141), Giza 2635 (146), Damietta 3018 (1057) , Menoufia 1905 (1081), Beni Suef 1679 (666), Kafr El-Sheikh 1696 (1313), Qena 1378 (222), Sohag 1495 (361), Assiut 1513 (250), Port Said 540 (202), Cairo 1272 (35), Sharqiah 492 (61) deaths, Ismailia 603 (28), Marsa Matrouh 110 (15), Al Wadi Al Jadid (New Valley) 247 (40), Fayoum 776 (55), Aswan 251 (67), Northern Sinai 1 (recovered). [An interactive map is available at
http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=11748; zoom in!].

Guidance is being provided to animal holders/breeders by the regional veterinary units regarding sanitary measures to be applied, including cleansing of premises, treatment of cadavers and other measures to be applied in order to eradicate the disease. -Mod. AS].

[Byline: Asha]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[According to several Egyptian newspapers of Sun 8 Apr 2012, new FMD cases and mortalities are continuing in several governorates, such as Menoufia, Kafr EL-sheikh and Qena. It may be assumed that the accurate accumulated number of infected/sick animals is higher than reported; mortality figures are easier to collect, their accuracy may well be higher. Cases in small ruminants are not included, probably because they are less likely to be clinically detected.

Clinical treatment of sick animals by visiting veterinarians is generally a step deserving caution; however, within heavily infected regions, the potential spread of the virus by mobile visitors is probably a less significant cause for concern. - Mod.AS].

